# TakeMeter Planning Document

## 1. Community Choice
I chose r/nba because NBA discourse is highly varied in quality.
The same topic can generate a detailed stat-heavy breakdown or a
one-sentence emotional outburst. This makes it ideal for a
classification task — the distinctions between post types are
real and meaningful to the community, not artificially imposed.

## 2. Label Taxonomy

### `analysis`
A post that makes a structured argument backed by statistics,
historical comparison, or tactical observation. The evidence is
specific and verifiable — it would support the claim even if
the opinion language were removed.

**Example 1:**
"Jokic's assist-to-turnover ratio this playoffs (5.2) is the
highest for any center in the last 20 years. His passing reads
under pressure are genuinely historic."

**Example 2:**
"The Celtics' defensive rating drops 8 points when Tatum guards
the opposing team's best perimeter player. That's why they keep
switching Brown onto Durant — the data backs it up."

---

### `hot_take`
A bold, confident opinion stated without real supporting evidence.
The post asserts rather than argues. Provocative framing is common.

**Example 1:**
"LeBron is the most overrated player in NBA history, full stop."

**Example 2:**
"This Warriors dynasty was always fake. They needed KD to win
and everyone knows it."

---

### `reaction`
An immediate emotional response to a specific event — a play,
trade, or game result. Little to no argument. The post is
expressing a feeling, not making a case.

**Example 1:**
"HOLY SHIT DID YOU SEE THAT DUNK I CANNOT BREATHE"

**Example 2:**
"I can't believe they traded him. Worst day of my life as a fan."

---

## 3. Hard Edge Cases

### Edge Case 1: The one-stat post
> "LeBron is overrated — his playoff win rate against
> top-seeded opponents is below .500."

Could be `hot_take` or `analysis`.

**Decision rule:** If the post uses one stat with accusatory
framing and no structured argument, label it `hot_take`.
A post needs more than one stat AND must be reasoning toward
a conclusion to qualify as `analysis`.

### Edge Case 2: The emotional analysis post
> "I'm so frustrated watching this team. Their pick-and-roll
> defense has been broken all season — they're giving up 1.2
> points per possession on that coverage, bottom-5 in the league."

Could be `reaction` or `analysis`.

**Decision rule:** If the post contains specific verifiable
evidence and is making an argument — even if emotionally
framed — label it `analysis`. Emotional tone does not
override substantive content.

## 4. Data Collection Plan
- **Source:** Reddit r/nba — top posts and comment threads
  from the last 6 months, collected manually
- **Target:** ~70 examples per label (210 total)
- **If a label is underrepresented:** Search specifically
  for that type using Reddit search terms listed in my notes
- **Will NOT collect:** Memes, image posts, posts under
  15 words, purely off-court news reposts

## 5. Evaluation Metrics
I will use:
- **Overall accuracy** — baseline correctness measure
- **Per-class F1** — because I care equally about all three
  labels and imbalance could hide poor performance on
  minority classes
- **Confusion matrix** — to identify which label pairs
  are confused and in which direction

Accuracy alone is not enough. A model predicting only
`hot_take` could still get 33%+ accuracy on a balanced
dataset. Per-class F1 exposes this. The confusion matrix
tells me which specific boundary the model hasn't learned.

## 6. Definition of Success
The classifier is useful if:
- Overall accuracy ≥ 70% on the test set
- No per-class F1 below 0.60
- Fine-tuned model beats zero-shot baseline by ≥ 10
  percentage points in overall accuracy

